            <div type="translation">
                <p>"Imperator Caesar, son of the divine Trajan Parthicus, grandson of the divine
                    Nerva, Trajan, Hadrian Augustus, chief priest, with tribunician power for the
                    twenty-first time, imperator for second time, consul for the third time, father of his country, (bids)
                    greetings to the Commons of the Macedonians. As you thought fit, let those who
                    are nominating others for office at the end of their own terms of office send
                    word within thirty days to those very men whom they will nominate for office.
                    Fabius Paternianus, Iulius Cassandrus, Attianus Alexandrus, Aelius Artemon (and)
                    Ulpius Lucianus served as envoys. Farewell. While those around Theodas, son of
                    Theodas, were serving as politarchs. In year 169 of Augustus."</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <!-- notes go here -->
                <p>Line 2: Νέρβα (genitive) is treated as indeclinable.</p>
                <p>Line 3: a little second
                    sigma and final omicron are used in Σεβαστός, apparently to finish the word on
                    that line.</p>
                <p>Line 6-7: τῶ Κοινῶ for classical τῶι Κοινῶι.</p>
                <p>Line 7: χαίριν for
                    classical χαίρειν appears to reflect the process of iotacism in the phonology
                    post-classical Greek (as with ἐκίνοις for classical ἐκείνοις on line 11).</p>
                <p>Line 11: as with Σεβαστός on line 3, the final sigma and alpha in προβάλλεσθαι are
                    both little, again apparently to finish the word on that line. </p>
                <p>Line 12: παρανγελλέτωσαν for classical παραγγελλέτωσαν. Only the orthography is
                    different, since in Attic, the initial gamma would also have been pronounced
                    nasally.</p>
                <p>Line 13-14: ἐπρέσβευεν has been considered by some to be mistaken.
                    However, it may be a perfectly good 3rd pl. imperf. act. ind. verb: in most
                    dialects outside of Attic-Ionic, and sometimes in Homer, the imperfect can have
                    active athematic secondary 3rd pl. endings in -εν such as ἔτιθεν. If the text is
                    actually mistaken, Occam's razor suggests that the word is a mistaken form of
                    the more classical form of the 3rd pl. imperf. act. ind. ἐπρέσβευον, which only
                    requires one change (ε should be ο) rather than the 3rd pl. aor. act. ind.
                    ἐπρέσβευσαν, which requires two changes (needs a σ where none is present, ε
                    should be α).</p>
                <p>Line 18: εὐτυχεῖτε is centred, with nothing else on its line.</p>
                <p>Line
                    19: dating formula is in smaller lettering size and indented, though not so far
                    indented as line 18. There is also an empty line both above and below it.</p>
                <p>Line 20: separated by an empty line from line 19 above it. If the editors'
                    restoration of [ἔτο]υς is correct, it is indented farther than line 19. From the
                    first word, there survives a cross-bar (such as the top stroke found on capital
                    pi, sigma and tau), a gap of approximately one character, then the top parts of
                    what appears to be an upsilon and sigma appear. The rest of the word is lost due
                    to the missing bottom-left corner of the front of the tablet. Given that numbers
                    follow + Σεβαστοῦ, clearly a dating formula, editors have confidently restored
                    the first word to [ἔτο]υς.</p>
            </div>
           
